			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">How to Run your Trak Raid<a name="60920"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 8 04 2:47 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I wrote this up for Molto, but I figure it should be publicly accessible.
<br />

<br />
Who's ready for the Trak raid?  
<br />

<br />
Before we do this, you should know exactly what you're getting into.  Trak is no cakewalk, even in his spawned version, and this kind of operation takes as long as 4 or 5 hours from when you give the word to gather till the last loot is handed out and you say goodbye.  Here's the rundown on how I do this:
<br />

<br />
<b>STEP 1: SPAWN CHECK</b>
<br />

<br />
Get someone who has a Singing Steel Helm to go to Old Sebilis and spawn check for you.  To do the spawn check, run to the wall, and right click your SS helm.  The eye cannot pop inside the wall, so it goes to a random place in Sebilis.  Have our Bind Sight song memmed.  Once you get an eye to pop inside Trak's lair, target one of the mobs there.  Then look around.  If Trak is up, you'll need to have another Trak hit the next day, and you'll need to kill him now.  If the UDB is up, you're a lucky duck, go on to step 2.  If neither are up, you're not gonna raid that night.
<br />

<br />
<b>STEP 2: SETUP.  </b> 
<br />

<br />
<i>2A:  Required Classes. </i>  Grab yourself an epic cleric, one mage per group (if you can), and a corpse summoner (SK or necro).  A main tank is nice, but not really needed for the final Trak fight.  Make sure you have some buffers along: a Shaman, Druid, and Enchanter is good.  After that, you need to fill up two groups.
<br />

<br />
The rest of the 12 slots needs to be filled with DPS is the name of the game.  You want to plow your way in fast, and kill Trak in under 1 minute.  Wizards, BL's, rogues, it's all good, really.  There will be some younglings who will want to go.  If you have the space, take them, but anyone under 55 who isn't a bard or doesn't know Sebilis will be more of a liability than a help.  Look for level 65 people first, then lower people.
<br />

<br />
Be sure to establish loot policy right from the get-go.  Even Trak loot is sometimes disputed.  If you're doing NBG, make sure that need is subject to your approval, or you'll get people rolling for their cousin or their alt.
<br />

<br />
<i>2B: Required Gear.</i>  Everyone coming must have gate gear.  That is to say, if they can't gate out, they need an OT hammer or gate potion.  If they have resist gear, tell them to bring it.
<br />

<br />
<i>2C:  Muster.</i>  Getting all your people to Sebilis can be a right pain in the butt.  Have a spare Sebilis key on you, and be ready to quest another in a hurry if more than one unkeyed chucklehead shows up.  People get lost on the way to Sebilis a LOT.  Ask around for helpers to show the way.
<br />

<br />
<i>2D:  Buffs.</i>  Don't waste time getting the perfect set of raid buffs.  You really won't need much on your way to Trak's lair beyond the basic HP buffs, haste, and crack for the casters.  Tell the other buffers to buff as mana permits, while you get moving.
<br />

<br />
<b>3:  MOVEMENT.</b>
<br />

<br />
<i>3A:  Command and Control.</i>  Establish a chat channel for the raid, where your people can ask general questions that aren't related to the tactical situation, where they can chat.  Keep the raid on a short leash.  Designate a main tank, and a puller who knows the route to Trak.  Make sure everyone understand what an assist button is and what to do with it.  Use raidchat for raid commands and coordination.  When possible and appropriate, use tells to keep people in line; public criticism just ticks people off and wastes time.
<br />

<br />
<i>3B:  Order of movement.</i>  Your puller should be the only one foraging ahead.  Your main tank should be at the front of the raid; no-one else should pass him unless a fight is in progress.  The whole raid MUST stick together and move together in Sebilis.  The mobs aren't hard, but people wandering around will get themselves and your raid killed in a hurry.  When charging a mob in place, the tank should move in first.  Keep a tight leash on them, and be careful NOT to engage the echo of Sebilis.
<br />

<br />
<i>3C: Pulling. </i>  The early stuff before you jump down into the water can be rushed easily enough.  Once you have jumped down and swum through the tunnel, though, keep it to single pulls.  An occasional add should be no problem.  Keep the pulls coming, avoid downtime; think LDoN-style.
<br />

<br />
<i>3D: Places of note. </i>  You should talk these spots through with your raid before they come to them.  Raids get hung up a lot at the following places on the way to Trak's lair: 
<br />
-At the ledge near the zone-in, where they have to jump down into the water, some people will be slow to do so, and won't see where to swim.  
<br />
-Swimming through the tunnels on the way to the mushroom area, plenty of people get disoriented.  
<br />
-Inside the Juggernaut fortress, there is a 1-way door; the puller will need someone reliable at the door there to click the pot and open it for him to pull through.
<br />
-Going through the fake wall just past the 1-way door, some people will go left; the proper way is right.
<br />
-On the ledge and bridge and ramp up to Trak's lair, people often fall off.  They have to move slowly and carefully there.
<br />

<br />
<b>4: The Trakanon Fight</b>
<br />
<i>4A: Trakanon info:</i> Trak is an undead dragon.  He hits for about 650 max, does an AE poisen DoT (kinda nasty), does an occasional 1500-point lifetap, and procs a banishment to the mushroom area.  He has roughly 30,000 hitpoints.
<br />

<br />
<i>4B:  If Trak is up,</i> you should pull all the juggs around there, pull Tolapumj, the hippy frog, rebuff, med up, and then rush Trak himself.  
<br />

<br />
<i>4C: If the UDB is up,</i> you can kill everything except him and set up for the fight right there in Trak's lair.  Buff, med up, and get runed before the fight starts; Trak will attack you first.  Do the turn-in, kill the UDB, and then Trak spawns.
<br />

<br />
<i>4D: Once you have engaged Trak</i>, burn him down as fast as possible.  Call for full discs when he gets down to 90% health, and full nukes right after.  If someone gets banished, they need to talk to their group mage, who should COTH them right back ASAP.  If no COTH is available, they should whip out their OT hammer and hope for a proc, or better yet, drink a gate potion.
<br />

<br />
<b>5:  RECOVERY</b>
<br />

<br />
<i>5A: The Corpse.</i>  As soon as Trak is down, get on the corpse, announce what dropped, and tell people to take their screenshots quickly.  
<br />

<br />
<i>5B: The Poisened, dead, and banished.</i>  Ask around for anyone who is still DoTed; they need to be cured ASAP.  Get the dead rezzed.  Ask around to see if anyone needs a COTH.  If someone has died away from the raid, they will need a corpse summoning and rez after loot is decided.  
<br />

<br />
<i>5C: Exodus.</i>  Everyone gets together, you AE TL out if possible, port out, or hammer out.  Make sure everyone gets out ok; if they are stuck there, you'll have to corpse summon and rez them.
<br />

<br />
<i>5D: Loot.</i>  Have all your looters link the spells and loot that dropped.  Decide loot however you like, but keep it quick; at this point, people are gonna want to head out.
<br />

<br />
<i>5E:  Corpse Runs:</i>  If there are any corpses left in Sebilis, pay for the coffins to get them out.  Take the corpse summoner and cleric that were with the raid and run them to Sebilis.  Never leave someone behind.
<br />

<br />
<b>6:  GET YOUR EPIC.</b>
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
